example.statement:
            For each set of values, find a function that has zeros at each value in the set.


\{0, 4\}

\{-2, 3\}

\{-1, 1, 3\}

ol.li:
The general model with the desired zeros is
           f(x) =ax(x-4)
           where a is a scaling parameter that will be determined
           using the given point. This is found by using x=1 and
           requiring an output of 2:

                f(1) = 2 \quad \hbox{and} \quad f(1) = a(1)(1-4) = -3a 
                -3a = 2 \quad \Rightarrow \quad a=-\frac{2}{3}

           So our function is given by
            f(x) = -\frac{2}{3}x(x-4). 



                   Graph of y=-2/3x(x-4).



                   \tikzset{%
                   }
                   \begin{tikzpicture}
                   \begin{axis}[
                       xmin=-2.2,xmax=5.2,
                       xtick={-2, -1, 0, 1, 2, 3, 4, 5},
                       xlabel={$x$},
                       ylabel={$y$},
                   ]

                   \addplot[blue, thick, samples=100]
                       ({x}, {-2/3*x*(x-4)});
                   \addplot[mark=none, black] {0};
                   \addplot[only marks, blue] table {
                       0 0
                       4 0
                       1 2
                   };
                   \end{axis}
                   \end{tikzpicture}

The desired model will be the same as the previous solution
           except multiplied by the parameter a:
           f(x) = a(x+2)(x-3).
           In order to guarantee that f(0)=3, we also require

                f(0) = a(0+2)(0-3) = -6a = 3 
                a=-\frac{1}{2}

           Consequently, the function is given by
            f(x) = -\frac{1}{2} (x+2)(x-3). 



                   Graph of y=-2/3x(x-4).



                   \tikzset{%
                   }
                   \begin{tikzpicture}
                   \begin{axis}[
                       xmin=-3.2,xmax=4.2,
                       xtick={-3, -2, -1, 0, 1, 2, 3, 4},
                       xlabel={$x$},
                       ylabel={$y$},
                   ]

                   \addplot[blue, thick, samples=100]
                       ({x}, {-1/2*(x+2)*(x-3)});
                   \addplot[mark=none, black] {0};
                   \addplot[only marks, blue] table {
                       -2 0
                       3 0
                       0 3
                   };
                   \end{axis}
                   \end{tikzpicture}

The function will be of the form
           f(x) = a(x+1)(x-1)(x-3),
           where a is determined by requiring f(2)=-6:

                f(2) = a(2+1)(2-1)(2-3) = a(3)(1)(-1) = -3a = -6 
                a=2

           Consequently, the function is given by
            f(x) = 2(x+1)(x-1)(x-3). 



                   Graph of y=-2/3x(x-4).



                   \tikzset{%
                   }
                   \begin{tikzpicture}
                   \begin{axis}[
                       xmin=-1.6,xmax=3.8,
                       xtick={-1, 0, 1, 2, 3},
                       xlabel={$x$},
                       ylabel={$y$},
                   ]

                   \addplot[blue, thick, samples=100]
                       ({x}, {2*(x+1)*(x-1)*(x-3)});
                   \addplot[mark=none, black] {0};
                   \addplot[only marks, blue] table {
                       -1 0
                       1 0
                       3 0
                       2 -6
                   };
                   \end{axis}
                   \end{tikzpicture}

example.statement:
Find the equation of a function that touches, but does not cross,
the x-axis at x=-2 and at x=3, and crosses
the axis at x=0, similar to the graph shown below, with
a value f(1)=5.



        Graph of a polynomial that touches the axis
        like a parabola at x=-2 and at x=3 and crosses
        the axes like a line at x=1 with f(1)=5.



        \tikzset{%
        }
        \begin{tikzpicture}
        \begin{axis}[
            xmin=-2.8,xmax=3.8,
            xtick={-2, -1, 0, 1, 2, 3},
            xlabel={$x$},
            ylabel={$y$},
        ]

        \addplot[blue, thick, samples=100]
            ({x}, {5/36*(x+2)^2*(x)*(x-3)^2});
        \addplot[mark=none, black] {0};
        \addplot[only marks, blue] table {
            -2 0
            0 0
            3 0
            1 5
        };
        \end{axis}
        \end{tikzpicture}

solution.p:
We find the scaling factor by making the function pass through the given point.
f(1) = a(1+2)^2(1)(1-3)^2 = a(9)(4) = 36a f(1) = 5 \quad \Rightarrow \quad 36a=5 \quad \Rightarrow \quad a=\frac{5}{36}
Consequently, our model for this graph would be f(x) = \frac{5}{36} x (x+2)^2(x-3)^2. The zero at x=0 has multiplicity 1, while the zeros at x=-2 and at x=3 each have multiplicity 2.

example.solution:
The graph of the parabola y=x^2 is shown below. Both ends of the
graph go up forever. So we say that y \to +\infty as x \to -\infty
(for the left side of the graph) and that y \to +\infty as
x \to +\infty (for the right side of the graph).




        Graph of y=x^2.



        \tikzset{%
        }
        \begin{tikzpicture}
        \begin{axis}[
            xmin=-4,xmax=4,
            xlabel={$x$},
            ylabel={$y$},
        ]

        \addplot[blue, thick, samples=100]
            ({x}, {x^2});
        \addplot[mark=none, black] {0};
        \end{axis}
        \end{tikzpicture}

The graph of the parabola y=x^3 is shown below. Because the
power is an odd integer, the sides of the graph go in opposite directions.
We say that y \to -\infty as x \to -\infty
(for the left side of the graph, which goes down) and that y \to +\infty as
x \to +\infty  (for the right side of the graph, which goes up).




        Graph of y=x^3.



        \tikzset{%
        }
        \begin{tikzpicture}
        \begin{axis}[
            xmin=-4,xmax=4,
            xlabel={$x$},
            ylabel={$y$},
        ]

        \addplot[blue, thick, samples=100]
            ({x}, {x^3});
        \addplot[mark=none, black] {0};
        \end{axis}
        \end{tikzpicture}

